Subject: Re: [Caml-list] unmarshaling large data from string on 32 bits

Hello,

Be aware when using the generic demarshaling on 32 bit systems with=20
large data (even when they fit in a string):  this will expand the heap=20
(adding more pages to it) on every demarshaling, and unless you arrange=20
so that the compacter runs often enough (calling manually Gc.compact for=20
instance), you'll end up eating all the memory.

This is documented here:

http://caml.inria.fr/mantis/view.php?id=3D5813

One possible work-around is to use an alternative implementation of the=20
demarshaler (there is such a pure OCaml implementation in Frama-C).=20
Another is to avoid the generic marshaling, either by writing a manual=20
version for your specific data type or by generating it from your type=20
definitions (=E0 la bin-prot, I assume).


Alain



